      <div class="deadline-box">
        <div class="deadline-box-label">Critical Deadline</div>
        <h3>Workforce Retention Grant Applications Due</h3>
        <p>ND critical access hospitals and owned/operated clinics must submit through ND HHS. Federal law requires the state to commit all Year One funds by end of October 2026 — leaving little margin for late applicants.</p>
        <div class="deadline-date">April 30, 2026 · 5:00 PM CT</div>
      </div>

      <p>Deputy Commissioner Emily O'Brien emphasized the state's intent to move fast and be a genuine partner to providers. "We want to make sure this process is easy and seamless," she said at the Rugby stakeholder meeting Tuesday. "And if it seems like it's not, we need to know." A public data dashboard will track grant deployment and outcomes for CMS reporting.</p>

      <div class="intel-box">
        <div class="intel-box-label">Von Halliday Analysis</div>
        <p>The April 30 deadline is tight. CAHs with limited grant-writing capacity are at real risk of leaving money on the table. Strong applications will need a clear theory of change, quantifiable retention metrics, and alignment with CMS's sustainability scoring rubric. The first-mover advantage is significant — subsequent rounds will be more competitive as more organizations get up to speed.</p>
      </div>
